<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Reconstruction">Reconstruction</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Akkadian_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Reconstruction">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Akkadian emphatic consonants are typically reconstructed as <a href="/wiki/Ejective_consonant" title="Ejective consonant">ejectives</a>, which are thought to be the oldest realization of emphatics across the Semitic languages.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> One piece of evidence for this is that Akkadian shows a development known as <a href="/wiki/Geers%27_law" title="Geers&#39; law">Geers' law</a>, where one of two emphatic consonants dissimilates to the corresponding non-emphatic consonant. For the sibilants, traditionally /≈°/ has been held to be postalveolar <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ É]</span>, and /s/, /z/, /<i lang="sem-Latn" title="Semitic languages romanization">·π£</i>/ analyzed as fricatives; but attested <a href="/wiki/Assimilation_(linguistics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Assimilation (linguistics)">assimilations</a> in Akkadian suggest otherwise.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_3-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> For example, when the possessive suffix <i>-≈°u</i> is added to the root <i>awat</i> ('word'), it is written <i>awassu</i> ('his word') even though <i>≈°≈°</i> would be expected. The most straightforward interpretation of this shift from <i>t≈°</i> to <i>ss</i> is that /s, ·π£/ form a pair of voiceless alveolar affricates <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[tÕ°s tÕ°s º]</span>, *≈° is a voiceless alveolar fricative <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[s]</span>, and *z is a voiced alveolar affricate or fricative <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[dÕ°z~z]</span>. The assimilation is then [awat+su] &gt; <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[awattÕ°su]</span>. In this vein, an alternative transcription of *≈° is *sÃ†, with the macron below indicating a soft (lenis) articulation in Semitic transcription. Other interpretations are possible, however. <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ É]</span> could have been assimilated to the preceding <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[t]</span>, yielding <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ts]</span>, which would later have been simplified to <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ss]</span>.
</p><p>The phoneme /r/ has traditionally been interpreted as a trill but its pattern of alternation with /<i lang="ar-Latn" title="DIN 31635 Arabic (Arabic language) transliteration">·∏´</i>/ suggests it was a velar (or uvular) fricative. In the Hellenistic period, Akkadian /r/ was transcribed using the Greek œÅ, indicating it was pronounced similarly as an <a href="/wiki/Dental,_alveolar_and_postalveolar_trills" class="mw-redirect" title="Dental, alveolar and postalveolar trills">alveolar trill</a> (though Greeks may also have perceived a <a href="/wiki/Uvular_trill" class="mw-redirect" title="Uvular trill">uvular trill</a> as œÅ).<sup id="cite_ref-:0_3-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Descent_from_Proto-Semitic">Descent from Proto-Semitic</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Akkadian_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Descent from Proto-Semitic">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Several <a href="/wiki/Proto-Semitic" class="mw-redirect" title="Proto-Semitic">Proto-Semitic</a> phonemes are lost in Akkadian. The Proto-Semitic glottal stop <i lang="sem-Latn" title="Semitic languages romanization"><a href="/wiki/Aleph_(letter)" class="mw-redirect" title="Aleph (letter)">* æ</a>, as well as the fricatives <a href="/wiki/Ayin" title="Ayin">* ø</a></i>, <i lang="sem-Latn" title="Semitic languages romanization"><a href="/wiki/He_(letter)" title="He (letter)">*h</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heth_(letter)" class="mw-redirect" title="Heth (letter)">*·∏•</a></i> are lost as consonants, either by sound change or orthographically, but they gave rise to the vowel quality <i>e</i> not exhibited in Proto-Semitic. The <a href="/wiki/Voiceless_lateral_fricatives" class="mw-redirect" title="Voiceless lateral fricatives">voiceless lateral fricatives</a> (<i lang="sem-Latn" title="Semitic languages romanization"><a href="/wiki/%C5%9Aawt" title="≈öawt">*≈õ</a>, <a href="/wiki/%E1%B8%8C%C4%81d" title="·∏åƒÅd">*·π£ÃÅ</a></i>) merged with the sibilants as in <a href="/wiki/Canaanite_languages" title="Canaanite languages">Canaanite</a>, leaving 19 consonantal phonemes. Old Akkadian preserved the /*≈õ/ phoneme longest but it eventually merged with <a href="/wiki/Shin_(letter)" title="Shin (letter)">/*≈°/</a>, beginning in the <a href="/wiki/First_Babylonian_dynasty" title="First Babylonian dynasty">Old Babylonian period</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_3-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> The following table shows Proto-Semitic phonemes and their correspondences among Akkadian, <a href="/wiki/Modern_Standard_Arabic" title="Modern Standard Arabic">Modern Standard Arabic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tiberian_Hebrew" title="Tiberian Hebrew">Tiberian Hebrew</a>:
</p>
