<td colspan="2">(as with 20?)
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Examples: erbƒì a≈°≈°ƒÅtum (four wives) (masculine numeral), meat ƒÅlƒÅn≈´ (100 towns).
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Syntax">Syntax</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Akkadian_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Syntax">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Nominal_phrases">Nominal phrases</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Akkadian_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Nominal phrases">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p><a href="/wiki/Adjectives" class="mw-redirect" title="Adjectives">Adjectives</a>, <a href="/wiki/Relative_clauses" class="mw-redirect" title="Relative clauses">relative clauses</a> and <a href="/wiki/Apposition" title="Apposition">appositions</a> follow the noun.
While <a href="/wiki/Numeral_(linguistics)" title="Numeral (linguistics)">numerals</a> precede the counted noun.
In the following table the nominal phrase <i>erbƒìt ≈°arr≈´ dann≈´tum ≈°a ƒÅlam ƒ´pu≈°≈´ ab≈´ya</i> 'the four strong kings who built the city are my fathers' is analyzed:
